t states of mind, far from being detached from the world, require a historical and cultural context for their very intelligibility.Available in English for the first time, this is the most outstanding work of one of France's finest contemporary philosophers. It provides a much-needed link between the continental and Anglo-American traditions, and its impact will extend beyond philosophy to anthropology, psychology, critical theory, and French studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPhilosophy of mind. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aAchilles' heel.  aAdult.  aAnachronism.  aAnalogy.  aAnthropologist.  aAristotelianism.  aAristotle.  aAutomaton.  aBehavior.  aBookkeeping.  aCausality.  aCerebrum.  aCognition.  aCognitive psychology.  aCognitivism (psychology).  aComputation.  aConcept.  aConceptual model.  aConsciousness.  aContemporary philosophy.  aConventional wisdom.  aDan Sperber.  aDatabase.  aDenis Diderot.  aDividend.  aDomestic worker.  aEdmund Husserl.  aEffectiveness.  aElectricity.  aEmpiricism.  aEnumeration.  aExplanation.  aFeeling.  aForeign policy of the United States.  aFormality.  aFrench philosophy.  aGenre.  aHolism.  aInstitut de France.  aInsurance law.  aIntelligent agent.  aIntention.  aIntentionality.  aIntersubjectivity.  aInvention.  aJerry Fodor.  aJohn Searle.  aLinguistic turn.  aLinguistics.  aLoaded language.  aLuc Ferry.  aMad scientist.  aMarshall Plan.  aMethodological solipsism.  aNachlass.  aNatural kind.  aNatural science.  aNet income.  aObstacle.  aPascal Engel.  aPayment.  aPersuasion.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy of Friedrich Nietzsche.  aPhilosophy of mind.  aPhilosophy.  aPhrase (music).  aPolitical philosophy.  aPr